#### Results

We compare our method with three existing works, OccNet \[ [29])\], ConvONet \[ [39])\] and IF-Net \[ [9])\].

The results can be found in Table [2]Table 2 â€£ 5 Reconstruction Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). We select 7 categories among 55 categories with largest training set ( _table, car, chair, airplane, sofa, rifle, lamp_). Detailed results can be found in the Appendix. We show different choices of Mğ‘€M. As we can see in this table, increasing Mğ‘€M from 646464 to 512512512 gives a performance boost. Even with the simplest model M=64ğ‘€64M=64, our results outperform ConvONet. The best results are achieved when setting M=512ğ‘€512M=512. In this case, our results lead in most categories when comparing to IF-Net. The results of IF-Net are better than ours in terms of metric F-Score in some categories. However, we argue that in this case the metric F-score is saturated (values are close to 111), which making it hard to compare. We also show results after introducing vector quantization to our model in the same table. We can see that vector quantization harms the performance slightly.

#### Qualitative Comparison

Qualitative results are shown in Fig. [6]Figure 6 â€£ Qualitative Comparison â€£ 5 Reconstruction Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). From the visualization, it can be seen that the reconstruction quality increases as Mğ‘€M increases, particularly for shapes with complex topology. OccNet, as a global latent method, often fails to recover complex structures. ConvONet can recover better structures than OccNet, due to its localized latents. By learning multiscale latents, IF-Net improves further upon ConvONet. Our method with M=64ğ‘€64M=64 outperforms ConvONet, and with M=128ğ‘€128M=128, the results are comparable with IF-Net.

