6 Generative Experiments.content:
We introduce three experiments to show how our model can be combined with auto-regressive transformers for generative modeling. In Sec. [6.1]Probabilistic Shape Reconstruction from a Single Image â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"), we show image-conditioned generation as probabilistic shape reconstruction from single image. In Sec. [6.2]Category-Conditioned Generation â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"), we show how we generate samples given a category label (using the 555555 ShapeNet categories). In Sec. [6.3]Point Cloud Conditioned Generation â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"), we further show generation conditioned on downsampled point clouds. In contrast to the first two tasks, the point-cloud-conditioned generation is based on a bidirectional transformer described in Sec [4.2]Bidirectional Transformer â€£ 4 Autoregressive Generative Modeling â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). More generative results on additional datasets ABO and D-FAUST can be found in the appendix.

### 6.1 Probabilistic Shape Reconstruction from a Single Image

We train a uni-directional transformer for this task (see Sec. [4.1]Unidirectional Transformer â€£ 4 Autoregressive Generative Modeling â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling")). The context ğ’ğ’\\mathcal{C} is an image. To train this model, we render 40 images (224Ã—224224224224\\times 224) of different views for each shape in ShapeNet. The implementation of the uni-directional transformer is based on GPT \[ [42])\]. It contains 24 blocks, where each block has an attention layer with 16 heads and 1024 embedding dimension. When sampling, nucleus sampling \[ [22])\] with top-pğ‘p (0.85) and top-kğ‘˜k (100) are applied to predicted token probabilities.

#### High resolution images.

We show some generated samples when ğ’ğ’\\mathcal{C} are high resolution images in Fig. [7]Figure 7 â€£ Low resolution images. â€£ 6.1 Probabilistic Shape Reconstruction from a Single Image â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). We compare our results with a deterministic method, OccNet \[ [29])\]. As we can see in the results, the deterministic method (OccNet) tends to create blurred meshes. However, our probabilistic reconstruction is able to output detailed meshes.

#### Low resolution images.

We also consider another more challenging task. The input images are downsampled to low resolution (16Ã—16161616\\times 16). In this case, the generative model has more freedom to find multiple plausible interpretations, including variations with different topology (see Fig. [8]Figure 8 â€£ Low resolution images. â€£ 6.1 Probabilistic Shape Reconstruction from a Single Image â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling")).

