### 6.2 Category-Conditioned Generation

To generate shapes given a category label, we use the context ğ’ğ’\\mathcal{C} to encode the category label. We employ the uni-directional transformer based on GPT as in Sec. [6.1]Probabilistic Shape Reconstruction from a Single Image â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). We compare to our proposed baseline model that encodes shapes as a latent grid of resolution 83superscript838^{3}. To make a fair comparison, we also extend ViT \[ [15])\] to the 3D voxel domain in the first stage of training. In the second stage, we use the same uni-directional transformer for sequence prediction. Here the sequence length is 83=512superscript835128^{3}=512, which is the same as in our proposed model. The baseline model is named Grid-83superscript838^{3}.
The comparison to the baseline model is in Fig. [9]Figure 9 â€£ 6.2 Category-Conditioned Generation â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). We can see that the baseline is unable to generate high quality shapes. We argue that this is because the representation is not expressive enough to capture surface details. Furthermore, we show more generated samples of our model in Fig. [10]Figure 10 â€£ 6.2 Category-Conditioned Generation â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). The three selected categories are _bookshelf, bench_ and _chair_. For both the baseline and our model, we render 101010 images of predicted shapes, and calculate the FrÃ©chet Inception Distance (FID) \[ [21]), [37])\] between predictions and test sets. The metrics can be found in Table [3]Table 3 â€£ 6.2 Category-Conditioned Generation â€£ 6 Generative Experiments â€£ 3DILG: Irregular Latent Grids for 3D Generative Modeling"). A perceptual study on the quality of generated samples can be found in the appendix.

