Shape completion
It is easy to adapt the 3D GAN inversion for the shape completion task.
In this experiment, we randomly drop 75% of the input point cloud ğ’™ğ’™\\bm{x} to train the encoder while keeping the loss functions unchanged. The trained encoder maps the incomplete input to a latent code that always corresponds to a plausible shape due to the GAN training. We can further optimize the latent code via minimizing [Eq.9]In 5 Applications â€£ SDF-StyleGAN: Implicit SDF-Based StyleGAN for 3D Shape Generation"). In [Fig.10]In 5 Applications â€£ SDF-StyleGAN: Implicit SDF-Based StyleGAN for 3D Shape Generation"), we test our method on the categories of chairs and airplanes and compare it with a state-of-the-art point completion cloud approach PoinTr \[ [YRWâˆ—21])\], which is based on a transformer architecture. We can see that within the shape space constrained by SDF-StyleGAN, our method has a better ability to reconstruct plausible shapes, even from a partial chair back (see [Fig.10]In 5 Applications â€£ SDF-StyleGAN: Implicit SDF-Based StyleGAN for 3D Shape Generation")-(a)). However, similar to the behavior on shape reconstruction, our method has worse capability in fitting fine details, such as the round joint of chair legs (see [Fig.10]In 5 Applications â€£ SDF-StyleGAN: Implicit SDF-Based StyleGAN for 3D Shape Generation")-(c)) and the wingtip of the airplane (see [Fig.10]In 5 Applications â€£ SDF-StyleGAN: Implicit SDF-Based StyleGAN for 3D Shape Generation")-(f)); while PoinTr keeps the original points to maintain the input geometry.

